        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 3,
          "name": "Mobile",
          "item": "https://toolkify.com/tools/mobile"
        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 4,
          "name": "Light Meter",
          "item": "https://toolkify.com/tools/mobile/light-meter"
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <!-- FAQ JSON-LD Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a light meter?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A light meter is a device or software application used to measure the intensity of light. In photography and cinematography, a light meter is primarily used to determine the correct exposure settings (aperture, shutter speed, and ISO) by measuring the amount of light falling on or reflected from a subject.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to use a light meter?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To use a physical light meter, set your desired ISO and shutter speed, then place the meter near your subject pointing towards either the light source (incident metering) or the subject (reflected metering) and press the measuring button. On a light meter app, simply grant camera access or use the built-in ambient light sensor, select your measurement mode, and read the real-time lux or relative brightness value to adjust your camera settings.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do you read a light meter?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Reading a light meter depends on the output type: digital meters show values directly in Lux, Foot-candles, or exposure parameters (like Ev or f-stop values). High numbers mean brighter light. You then match this reading with your camera's exposure scale or use an exposure calculator to determine the recommended aperture and shutter speed combination.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to use light meter app?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To use a light meter app, open the application on your smartphone and select either the sensor mode (if your phone has a native ambient light sensor) or the camera mode. Position your phone's sensor or camera towards the light source or the subject. The app will display the light level in Lux or relative percentage. You can then use the built-in calculators to find the suggested ISO, aperture, and shutter speed for photography.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does a light meter work?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A light meter works by using a photosensitive sensor (such as a silicon photodiode or camera sensor) to capture incoming photons. The sensor converts this light energy into an electrical signal, which is processed by internal circuitry or software algorithms to produce a readable measurement of light intensity, typically expressed in Lux (lx) or Foot-candles (fc).</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does a light meter do?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A light meter measures illuminance or luminance to help photographers, filmmakers, light designers, and horticulturists assess light levels. It eliminates guesswork by providing precise values of light intensity, ensuring accurate camera exposures, appropriate workplace lighting conditions, or optimal light levels for plant growth.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

