        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          1. Honest Sensor Accuracy & API Limits
        </h4>
        <p>
          The Ambient Light Sensor API provides standard, calibrated illuminance values in Lux. However, this API is disabled by default in most desktop browsers and is completely unsupported on iOS Safari due to user-fingerprinting protection.
        </p>
        <p>
          If the Ambient Light Sensor is unavailable, the application automatically switches to <strong>Camera Estimate</strong>. This fallback reads live camera video frames using canvas image data to compute average pixel luminance. Because cameras auto-adjust ISO, aperture, and shutter speed on the fly, <em>a camera estimate cannot represent calibrated Lux</em>. We clearly present it on a relative 0â€“100 scale to prevent misleading readouts.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          2. How We Calculate Camera Brightness
        </h4>
        <p>
          In Camera Estimate mode, video frames are sampled at a rate of 3 times per second onto an offscreen canvas. We parse the RGBA values of each pixel and compute luminance using standard BT.601 coefficients:
        </p>
        <code class="block bg-surface p-2 border border-hairline rounded text-[10px] text-primary">
          Luminance = 0.299*R + 0.587*G + 0.114*B
        </code>
        <p>
          These average values are smoothed using a rolling simple moving average to filter out camera auto-exposure focus jumps.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          3. Absolute Privacy Sandbox
        </h4>
        <p>
          All operations occur locally in your browser workspace. Camera media streams are bound dynamically to local canvas targets, and we ensure the camera stream releases completely the second you pause the capture, click Reset, or close the page.
        </p>

